WorkItem.Description:
Consider the following:

```
module A {
	class A {}
	export var x = 1;
}
```

In TypeScript this code looks quite innocuous but if we look at the generated JavaScript:

```
var A;
(function (A) {
    var A = (function () {
        function A() {
        }
        return A;
    })();
    A.x = 1;
})(A || (A = {}));
```

We see that inside the module function the class variable A overrides the parameter A referencing the module, causing every export declaration after the class declaration to be exported on the class instead of the module.

The same goes for interfaces, enums, etc. Anything that causes var A; to be emitted inside a function(A) { â€¦ } context.

Given that the TypeScript code compiles without error or warning and that this pattern of having types inside modules with the same name is quite common I consider this a rather serious bug.

Comments.Message:
New codegen detects this and will rename the module parameter until it works:

```
var A;
(function (_A) {
    var A = (function () {
        function A() {
        }
        return A;
    })();
    _A.x = 1;
})(A || (A = {}));
```
